<hr><br><a name=books></a>
<font size=5>Recommended Frost Books</font>
<br><ul>
<li>
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0805005013/ubriacowinerevie" target="top">
The Collected Poems, Complete and Unabridged (1979)</a><br>
Complete, Unabridged, all poems, 607 pages, and a no frills $14 price.  This is the thing. <br><br>

<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0671496174/ubriacowinerevie" target="top">
Robert Frost's Poems (1991)</a><br>
This is the book for people who want all the Frost poems that can fit in a nice, little $5 book.  <br><br>

<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0486275507/ubriacowinerevie" target="top">
The Road Not Taken and Other Poems (1993) </a><br>
This is so cool, a book of Frost Poem's for only 80 cents.  It has about 30-40 poems, you can follow the link and see which ones.  What do I do when confronted with a cool little book that only costs 80 cents?  Well, I buy about 10 and give them away to people for fun.  And don't limit it to people you like.  It's actually much better to give a copy to all your worst enemies.  Now that's good fun.<br><br>

<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1559945664/ubriacowinerevie" target="top">
Robert Frost Reads (1992)</a><bR>
What about Frost reading his poems?  Is that cool?  Well, if they're going to be read aloud, why not let it be the man himself.  Almost 2 hours on 2 tapes.<br><br>

<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0252023382/ubriacowinerevie" target="top">
The Ordeal of Robert Frost : The Poet and His Poetics (1997) </a><br>
 I've heard good things about this book, although I haven't yet read it myself.  I wanted to mention it, however, in case anyone who's super-interested in Frost wants to take a chance.  I'll probably get it sooner or later and let you know for sure if it's worth it.  
</ul>

